<subSubSection pageId="145" pageNumber="146" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="145.[151,1437,722,1719]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1334,1359]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Remarks.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carter" authorityYear="1871" box="[443,589,1334,1359]" class="Calcarea" family="Trichogypsiidae" genus="Trichogypsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Baerida" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[443,589,1334,1359]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Trichogypsia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is so far confined to the North Atlantic and North Pacific. Following 
<bibRefCitation pageId="145" pageNumber="146" refId="ref66090" refString="Dendy, A. &amp; Row, R. W. H. (1913) The classification and phylogeny of the Calcareous Sponges, with a reference list of all the described species, systematically arranged. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1913 (3), 704 - 813. Available from: http: // onlinelibrary. wiley. com / doi / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1913. tb 06152. x / full (accessed 21 January 2018)" type="journal article">Dendy &amp; Row (1913)</bibRefCitation>
, the World Porifera Database (Van 
<bibRefCitation box="[717,907,1370,1395]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" refId="ref69887" refString="van Soest, R. W. M., Boury-Esnault, N., Hooper, J. N. A., Rutzler, K., de Voogd, N. J., Alvarez de Glasby, B., Hajdu, E., Pisera, A. B., Manconi, R., Schoenberg, C., Janussen, D., Tabachnick, K. R., Klautau, M., Picton, B., Kelly, M., Vacelet, J., Dohrmann, M., Diaz, M. C., Cardenas, P., Carballo, J. L., Rios, P. &amp; Downey, R. (2018) World Porifera database. Available from: http: // www. marinespecies. org / porifera (accessed 21 January 2018)" type="journal article">
Soest 
<emphasis box="[785,841,1370,1395]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
) recognizes three distinct species. In the North Atlantic there are Southern England’s 
<taxonomicName authority="Carter, 1871" authorityName="Carter" authorityYear="1871" box="[599,859,1406,1431]" class="Calcarea" family="Clathrinidae" genus="Leucetta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[599,705,1406,1431]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">T. villosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[716,859,1407,1431]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" refId="ref64774" refString="Carter, H. J. (1871) A description of two new Calcispongiae, to which is added confirmation of Prof. James Clark's discovery of the true form of the sponge-cell (animal), and an account of the polype-like pore area of Cliona corallinoides contrasted with Prof. E. Hackel's view on the relationship of the sponges to the corals. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4, 8 (43), 1 - 27. Available from: https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 63424  page / 15 / mode / 1 up (accessed 21 January 2018)" type="journal article">Carter, 1871</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and Southern Norwegian 
<taxonomicName authority="(Haeckel, 1872)" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1872" baseAuthorityName="Haeckel" baseAuthorityYear="1872" class="Calcarea" family="Trichogypsiidae" genus="Trichogypsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Baerida" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="incrustans">
<emphasis box="[1169,1315,1407,1430]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">T. incrustans</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation pageId="145" pageNumber="146" refId="ref66738" refString="Haeckel, E. (1872) Die Kalkschwamme. Eine Monographie in zwei Banden Text und einem Atlas mit 60 Tafeln Abbildungen. Vol. 1 - 3. G. Reimer, Berlin, 484 pp., 418 pp. &amp; 60 pls. Available from: https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 44605  page / 5 / mode / 1 up (accessed 13 March 2018)" type="book chapter">Haeckel, 1872</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, originally as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1872" box="[379,482,1444,1467]" class="Calcarea" family="Trichogypsiidae" genus="Leucyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Baerida" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[379,482,1444,1467]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Leucyssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This contrasts with Burton’s (1963) opinion that the two are conspecific. Borojević 
<emphasis box="[151,209,1478,1503]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">et al.</emphasis>
(2000) have re-examined only Carter’s (1871) slide, remarking that the internal canals are lined by special curved spicules, not noted by Carter. In the absence of a redescription of Haeckel’s material, we remain in doubt over the specific differences. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation box="[591,858,1550,1575]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" refId="ref67708" refString="Lehnert, H. &amp; Stone, R. P. (2017) Description of a new species of Trichogypsiidae (Porifera, Calcarea) and first record of the genus in the Pacific Ocean. Zootaxa, 4312 (2), 394 - 400. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4312.2.13" type="journal article">Lehnert &amp; Stone (2017)</bibRefCitation>
described a further species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lehnert &amp; Stone" authorityYear="2017" box="[1168,1435,1550,1575]" class="Calcarea" family="Trichogypsiidae" genus="Trichogypsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Baerida" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="alaskensis">
<emphasis box="[1168,1435,1550,1575]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Trichogypsia alaskensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the S coast of Alaska. In any case, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carter" authorityYear="1871" box="[638,742,1586,1611]" class="Calcarea" family="Clathrinidae" genus="Leucetta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[638,742,1586,1611]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">T. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Haeckel" baseAuthorityYear="1872" box="[806,953,1588,1611]" class="Calcarea" family="Trichogypsiidae" genus="Trichogypsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Baerida" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="incrustans">
<emphasis box="[806,953,1588,1611]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">T. incrustans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(greyish white or greenish white) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lehnert &amp; Stone" authorityYear="2017" class="Calcarea" family="Trichogypsiidae" genus="Trichogypsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Baerida" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="alaskensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">T. alaskensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(golden brown) differ from the 
<collectingCountry box="[638,758,1622,1647]" name="Seychelles" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
specimen (red) in life color. Spicule lengths of the present specimen are 120–530 µm, Carter and Haeckel give 200–450 µm for the two European species, so these match closely. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lehnert &amp; Stone" authorityYear="2017" box="[242,385,1694,1719]" class="Calcarea" family="Trichogypsiidae" genus="Trichogypsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Baerida" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="alaskensis">
<emphasis box="[242,385,1694,1719]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">T. alaskensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has much larger spicules, up to 1225 
<date box="[808,857,1694,1719]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" value="1946-10">x 46</date>
µm.
</paragraph>
